Introduction To Deliverable 3

For my Data Science project, I would like to take movies and try to see if I can predict a movies genre based off the summery of the movie to answer the question Can you predict a genre of a movie based of a overview or summery of the movie? I will define it as a success if I can find a trend in one genre that differs from other genre trends.

The data set I will be using will be a movie data set form TMDB (The Movie Data Base). The set contains over 45,000 data entries and 24 attributes. I will be using 11 of those attributes and be building more attributes from that data.

A weakness of the data set will be the 0 or null values for data points. Some are missing one or two attributes but have the rest of them. That is going to take a toll to my calculations when I try to compute an average or quantile of the whole data set.

Here are some important data attributes I will be using

genre - string - The genre of the movie. Can contain multiple

id - integer - Unique number id for the movie

overview - string - A description of the movie

popularity - double - The popularity of the movie

original_title - string - Title

vote_average - double - Average ratings the movie received.

vote_count - integer - The count of votes received.

#Data Analysis

Converts string version of list of dict if id(int) and names(string) from python to a char array of just the ids and names Only works if id is int and name is string

#converts string version of list of dict if id(int) and names(string) from python to a char array of just the ids and names
#only works if id is int and name is string
ldictToDf <- function(tempList){
  tempList <- gsub("name","'", tempList)
  tempList <- gsub("id","'", tempList)
  tempList <- strsplit(tempList, "")[[1]]
  tempString <- c()
  for(x in seq(length(tempList))){
    if (tempList[x] != " " &tempList[x] != "," & tempList[x] != '}' & tempList[x] != '{' & tempList[x] != "'" 
        & tempList[x] != ":"){
      tempString <- c(tempString, tempList[x])
    }
  }
  tempString <- tempString[-length(tempString)]
  tempString <- tempString[-1]
  idMovies <- c()
  nameMovies <- c()
  tempId <- ""
  tempName <- ""
  #False = id, True = name
  
  isnum <- TRUE
  for (ind in seq(length(tempString))) {
    if(isnum == TRUE){
      if(tempString[ind] >= '0' & tempString[ind] <= '9'){
        tempId <- paste(tempId,tempString[ind], sep = "")
      }
      else{
        idMovies <- c(idMovies,tempId)
        tempId <- ""
        isnum = FALSE
        tempName <- paste(tempName,tempString[ind],sep = "")
      }
    }
    else{
      if(tempString[ind] >= '0' & tempString[ind] <= '9'){
        nameMovies <- c(nameMovies,tempName)
        tempName <-""
        tempId <- paste(tempId,tempString[ind],sep = "")
        isnum = TRUE
      }
      else{
        if(tempString[ind] != '|'){
          tempName <- paste(tempName,tempString[ind],sep = "")
        }
      }
    }
  }
  nameMovies <- c(nameMovies,tempName)

  return(data.frame("id"= as.integer(idMovies), "name" = nameMovies))
}


movieTibble$genre_ids <- NA
movieTibble$genre_names <- NA

movieTibble$genre_names <- as.list(movieTibble$genre_names) 

for(x in seq(length(movieTibble[[1]]))){
  if(nchar(movieTibble[["genres"]][x]) < 3){
    movieTibble[["genre_ids"]][x] <- list(-1)
    movieTibble[["genre_names"]][x] <- list("None")
  }
  else{
    tempDF = ldictToDf(movieTibble[["genres"]][x])
    movieTibble[["genre_ids"]][x] <- list(unname(unlist( tempDF[1]) ) )
    movieTibble[["genre_names"]][x] <- list(unname(unlist( tempDF[2]) ) )
  }
}

#adds weighted rating to each movie based on IMDB' weighted rating. Used to balance voting averages with movies with a small number of votes
createWR <- function(votes, minVotes, avgRating, meanVote){
  return( ( ( votes/(votes+minVotes) )*avgRating) + ( (minVotes/(votes+minVotes) )*meanVote))
}

topChartTibble <-topChartTibble %>%
  mutate(weightedRating =  createWR(vote_count,minimumVoteCount,vote_average, meanVote))

#Print out top 10 rated movies
topChartTibble %>% arrange(desc(weightedRating)) %>%
  select(original_title,weightedRating,popularity,vote_average,vote_count) %>%
  head(10)

Now i can create a function what spits out top movies given a genre

topInGenre <- function(genreName){
  temp <- topChartTibble %>% 
    arrange(desc(weightedRating)) %>%
    filter(genre_names %>% 
             map(str_detect, genreName) %>%
             map_lgl(any)) %>%
    select(original_title,weightedRating,popularity,vote_average,vote_count,genre_names) %>%
    head(10)
  temp$genre_names <- genreName
  return(temp)
}

Now can create a Term Frequency Inverse Document Frequency with all the words in all the summeries

#calculate termFrequency function
term.freq <- function(r){
  r/sum(r)
}

#calculate inverse document frequency

i.d.f <- function(c){
  size = length(c)
  document.size <- length(which(c>0))
  
  log10(size/document.size)
}


#combine functions to get tf-idf

tfidf <- function(termf,idf){
  termf*idf
}

#run the term.freq function against the rows
train.tokens.df <- apply(train.tokens.matrix, 1, term.freq)

This next part is a bit tricky. The library lsa has a cosine simularity function but it can only be used with two vectors where it compares them together or one full matrix where it compares each row to each other. So I took the data frame of the TF-IDF and created a martrix with it remove the titles of each row. Then I created a tibble with an index, similarity score, and a label. The label will be the title.

For those specific instance I decided to use the first row in the dataframe and compare it to all the other rows in a for loop, and then stored the score with the corespoding title in the cosine.score.tibble

cosine.matrix <-data.matrix(train.tokens.tfidf.df[,2:dim(train.tokens.tfidf.df)[2]])


cosine.score.tibble <- tibble(index = integer(), score = numeric(), label = character())

for (x in seq(2:dim(train.tokens.tfidf.df)[1])) {
  tempScore <- cosine(c(cosine.matrix[x,1:dim(cosine.matrix)[2]]),c(cosine.matrix[1,1:dim(cosine.matrix)[2]] ))[1]
  cosine.score.tibble <- cosine.score.tibble %>% add_row(index = x, score = tempScore, label = train.tokens.tfidf.df[x,1])
}

cosine.score.tibble %>% arrange(-score)

Now we see in our data that we have copies of each movie with their specified genre

we can train our model now with stratified cross validation because the representation of each genre is not proportional to each other meaning that we dont have an equal or close to equal number of movies for each genre so we wanna train out model with that in account

Were going to do 10 fold cross validation 3 times because we can get more accurate results as long as we can take the computational hit time wise Used the Labels to select the correct proportions of the genres

cv.folds <- createMultiFolds(testTokens$Label, k=10, times = 3)

cv.trainModel <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10,repeats = 3, index = cv.folds)


train.part.1 <- train(Label ~ .,data = testTokens, method = "rpart", trControl = cv.trainModel, tuneLength = 7 )

Here we see the results of the trained model cp is the complexity parameter which tries to control the size, number of splits, of the tree. The default value starts at 0.01 and adjusts every resampling to to try and improve accuracy

The Accuracy is how accurate our model is to predicting the genre of the movie

And the Kappa is a metric that compares observed Accuracy with an Expected accuracy Its not relevant enough to describe for this model

I would like to go back to the cosine similarity score between the movies and make a new tibble with the scored for each movie. Instead of putting the movies as the columns too making it number of movies by number of movies, i want to calculate the scores and then add up the scored that came from one genre and divide by the number of movies from that genre, giving me the average similarity score from that genre to that movie and making the tibble number of movies by number of genres.

The goal of this approach is to see if the average similarity score of a movie from other movies in the same genre is significantly higher than other average genre similarity scores

#Now were going to double for loop through all the movies comparing them all

#takes about 15 minutes

cosine.matrix <-data.matrix(train.tokens.tfidf.df[,2:dim(train.tokens.tfidf.df)[2]])


for (x in seq(1:dim(train.tokens.tfidf.df)[1])) {
  for (y in seq(1:dim(train.tokens.tfidf.df)[1])) {
    if(!(x == y)){
      
      tempScore <- cosine(c(cosine.matrix[x,1:dim(cosine.matrix)[2]]),c(cosine.matrix[y,1:dim(cosine.matrix)[2]] ))[1]
      genreLocations <- match(workTibble$genre_names[[y]], allgenres)
      for(z in genreLocations){
        sim.score.avgs[x,z+1] <- sim.score.avgs[x,z+1]  + tempScore
      }
    }
    
  }
}


#Here we can see the summation of all the comparisons
sim.score.avgs[1:10,1:10]

Now we divide to the numbers of ratings were added to that movie. We can do this by adding up the movies in a certain genre and when dividing, subtract 1 from the denominator if that movie is part of that genre, other wise, just divide by the number of movies in that genre

genre.counts <- rep(0,times=length(allgenres))

for (x in seq(length(workTibble[[1]]))) {
  genre.indexes <- c(match(c(workTibble$genre_names[[x]]), allgenres))
  for(ind in genre.indexes){
    genre.counts[ind] <- genre.counts[ind] + 1
  }
}

sim.score.saved <- sim.score.avgs
for (x in seq(1:dim(sim.score.avgs)[1])) {
  genreLocations <- c(match(workTibble$genre_names[[x]], allgenres))
  for (y in c(seq(2:dim(sim.score.avgs)[2])+1)) {
    if ( !( (y-1) %in% genreLocations) ){
      sim.score.avgs[x,y] <- sim.score.avgs[x,y]/genre.counts[y-1]
    }
    else{
    sim.score.avgs[x,y] <- sim.score.avgs[x,y]/(genre.counts[y-1] -1)
    }
  }
}

sim.score.avgs[1:10,1:10]
#and now we the averages of each score for the corresponding genre

Im going to finish off with going through the similarity score and collecting 1) a binary yes or no if one of a movies genres is the highest score and 2) a decimal value of how many of the movie genres were the highest score ill be taking the number of genre the movies has, taking that number of highest scores, and dividing the number of genres that are in the highest scores by the number of possible genres

sim.selection.scores <- tibble(title = character(),
                               top.genre.sim.score = logical(),
                               top.genre.sim.score.percent = numeric())

sim.score.avgs$Foreign[is.na(sim.score.avgs$Foreign)] <- 0
#aparently there were no foreign films in the dataset but thats ok. We just need 
#to assign those values to 0 because the max function doesnt do well with NA values

for (x in seq(1:dim(sim.score.avgs)[1])) {
  max.indexes <- order(unlist(unname(sim.score.avgs[x,2:(dim(sim.score.avgs)[2]-1)])),decreasing = T)
  genreLocations <- c(match(workTibble$genre_names[[x]], allgenres))
  is.max.genre <- FALSE
  if(max.indexes[1] %in% genreLocations){
    is.max.genre <- TRUE
  }
  max.count <- sum(max.indexes[1:length(genreLocations)] %in% genreLocations) / length(genreLocations)
  
  sim.selection.scores <- sim.selection.scores %>%
    add_row(title = workTibble$original_title[[x]],
            top.genre.sim.score = is.max.genre,
            top.genre.sim.score.percent = max.count)
  
}

sim.selection.scores
#and we an check the percentage of movies that had on of their genres as the top 
#similarity score
top.sim.percent <- sum(sim.selection.scores$top.genre.sim.score) / length(sim.selection.scores[[1]])
